{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17510577","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17510577"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:31:53+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:31:53+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11593"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11593","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11593"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.06,0.08,0.76,0.03,0.07]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4220"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106250"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4220","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4220"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11593"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88718"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"13"},{"type":"tags","id":"23"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"2166"},{"type":"tags","id":"4187"},{"type":"tags","id":"4340"},{"type":"tags","id":"4345"},{"type":"tags","id":"4517"},{"type":"tags","id":"4980"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11634"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"},{"type":"tags","id":"12920"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"17467"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17643"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27044"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27052"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39115"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39129"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43254"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44281"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106250","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/106250"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 32-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic at 12 weeks\u0027 gestation with her first pregnancy. The pregnancy has been progressing smoothly, and she has attended all her antenatal appointments. She is rhesus negative and has been reading online about some \u0027injections\u0027 that she needs because of this. She is very nervous about her blood group negatively affecting the baby and seeks advice.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EShe has had a blood group and antibodies with her antenatal booking bloods which reveal that her blood group is Rh -ve with no antibodies. She has had non-invasive prenatal testing (NIPT) which has confirmed the fetal blood group is O positive. She lives in a rural area.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate plan for her?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["She needs an anti-D injection right now and at 28 weeks","Reassure her that no further management is needed","She needs anti-D injections at 28 and 34 weeks gestation","She should get an anti-D injection regardless of her antibodies","She should repeat NIPT at 28 weeks and 34 weeks gestation"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EAnti-D (rhesus immunoglobulin) is given to rhesus negative women during pregnancy who do not have preformed anti-D antibodies. More recently NIPT has been used to confirm if the fetus is a positive or negative blood group - allowing selection of which women need anti-D. If the fetus is a positive blood group as in this case (O+ve) then the mother requires anti-D injections. A blood test at the booking visit is done to confirm the woman\u0027s blood group and if she has any antibodies (such as anti-D). If a woman has pre-formed anti-D antibodies she should not receive an anti-D injection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EShe needs anti-D injections at 28 and 34 weeks gestation\u003C/strong\u003E is the correct answer. Routine administration of anti-D during pregnancy includes 625IU at 28 and 34 weeks, as well as 625IU postpartum if the baby is rhesus positive. This is a routine part of antenatal care for rhesus negative women carrying a rhesus positive fetus to prevent sensitisation and potential haemolytic disease of the newborn in future pregnancies.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EShe needs an anti-D injection right now\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect because there is no indication for an immediate anti-D injection at 12 weeks unless there has been a sensitising event (e.g., miscarriage, chorionic villus sampling, abdominal trauma), which is not mentioned in the stem. For sensitising events, 250IU is given in the first trimester and 625IU beyond the first trimester, ideally within 72 hours of the event.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReassure her that no further management is needed\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect because, as a rhesus negative woman with a rhesus positive fetus, she requires anti-D injections at specific gestational weeks to prevent potential complications in future pregnancies. Without anti-D prophylaxis, she is at risk of developing antibodies against fetal red blood cells.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EShe should get an anti-D injection regardless of her antibodies\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect because if a woman already has preformed anti-D antibodies (not due to previous anti-D administration), giving anti-D immunoglobulin would not be beneficial as sensitisation has already occurred. In this case, the patient does not have preformed antibodies, so she should receive anti-D at the appropriate times.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EShe should repeat NIPT at 28 weeks and 34 weeks gestation\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect because there is no clinical indication to repeat NIPT for fetal blood typing. NIPT is highly accurate for determining fetal blood type, and a single test is sufficient. NIPT does not reveal whether there are maternal antibodies to anti-D - a blood group and antibodies test is required to assess this. The focus should be on providing appropriate anti-D prophylaxis based on the already confirmed fetal rhesus status.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Anti-D immunoglobulin should be given to all rhesus negative women with a rhesus positive fetus at 28 and 34 weeks gestation and after any sensitising event.","Rh(D) immunoglobulin should not be given to women with preformed Anti-D antibodies except when the antibodies are due to previous antenatal administration of Rh(D) immunoglobulin.","Anti-D prevents maternal antibody formation against fetal red blood cells, preventing haemolytic disease of the newborn in current and future pregnancies."],"references":["National Blood Authority. \u0022Guidelines on the prophylactic use of RhD immunoglobulin (anti-D) in obstetrics\u0022. 2003. Access at: https://www.blood.gov.au/system/files/documents/glines-anti-d.pdf.","SA Maternal, Neonatal \u0026 Gynaecology Community of Practice 2020. Anti-D Prophylaxis. The Government of South Australia: SA Health. Access at: https://www.sahealth.sa.gov.au/wps/wcm/connect/1d9012804ee1d743ac48add150ce4f37/anti%2Bd%2Bprophylaxis_29042016.pdf?MOD=AJPERES\u0026amp;CACHEID=ROOTWORKSPACE-1d9012804ee1d743ac48add150ce4f37-nGzK28o.","Oyelowo, T.. Mosby\u0027s guide to women\u0027s health: A handbook for health professionals. 2007. Elsevier Health Sciences.","Costumbrado J, Mansour T, Ghassemzadeh S. Rh Incompatibility. [Updated 2024 May 7]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK459353/","RANZCOG. Guidelines for the use of Rh(D) Immunoglobulin (Anti-D) in obstetrics (C-Obs 6). June 2024. ranzcog.edu.au. [Internet]. Accessed on 12 Jan 2025. Available from: https://ranzcog.edu.au/wp-content/uploads/Anti-D-Guidelines.pdf"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88718"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11593"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88718","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/88718"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-17T09:20:47+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-17T10:57:28+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4220"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106250"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"13","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/13"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\ude78","name":"Haematology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:44+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"23","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/23"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd30","name":"Obstetrics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{